{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"23abd893-76fa-400a-af51-292c0b2e2ee2","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or anywhere you configure the app builder):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on Android stop */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Requirements:**\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- The `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` directives ensure platform code only compiles on the target platform.\n\nYou can also subscribe to the cross-platform `Window.Deactivated` event for a unified (but less granular) approach, or override methods directly in a custom `MauiUIApplicationDelegate` (iOS) / `MauiAppCompatActivity` (Android) in the respective `Platforms/` folders.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"46525c18-83b1-4032-ba77-1efb50eb9540","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"E84E:DF52E:2743C0E:2B4B699:69F93EF8"},"id":"89a0d4ce-cb16-46e6-b459-3bcc586447aa","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:51:13.467Z","parentId":"ba5ca1d6-9754-4028-b35e-bbefbe1420e4"}
